==Merged second translation== [[ja:]] '''Harenaga Tsuchimikado''' (土御門 晴栄, formerly written as 土御門 &#x6674;榮; June 30, 1859 – October 16, 1915) was a Japanese {{ill|onmyōji|ja|陰陽師|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/onmyōji|qq=}} and politician. He held the title of {{ill|Viscount (Japan)|ja|子爵|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Viscount (Japan)|qq=}} and was posthumously awarded the Rank of {{ill|Senior Third Rank|ja|正三位|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Senior Third Rank|qq=}}. His childhood name was '''Kazumaru''' (和丸), and his birth surname was '''Nishigori''' (錦織). His name is sometimes read as "Hareyoshi."
He served as an official overseeing astronomy and the calendar, and later became a member of the {{ill|House of Peers (Japan)|ja|貴族院|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/House of Peers (Japan)|qq=}}, serving three terms.
== Biography == === Early Life === Born as the second son of {{ill|Nishigori Hisataka|ja|錦織久隆|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nishigori Hisataka|qq=}}, a {{ill|kuge|ja|公家|1=Kuge|qq=|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/kuge|qq=}} noble, Harenaga was descended from the {{ill|Tsuchimikado clan|lt=Tsuchimikado clan|lt=Tsuchimikado family|ja|土御門家|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tsuchimikado family|qq=}}, known for their roles in {{ill|astronomy|ja|天文道|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/astronomy|qq=}}, {{ill|calendar making|ja|暦道|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/calendar making|qq=}}, and {{ill|onmyōdō|ja|陰陽道|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/onmyōdō|qq=}}. His ancestry traced back to prominent figures such as {{ill|Abe no Seimei|ja|安倍晴明|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Abe no Seimei|qq=}}. He married into the Tsuchimikado family, becoming the adopted son of {{ill|Tsuchimikado Haruo|ja|土御門晴雄|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tsuchimikado Haruo|qq=}} and assuming the family headship after Haruo’s death in 1869.
=== As an Onmyōji === After succeeding as the head of the Tsuchimikado family, Harenaga faced difficulties due to the abolition of traditional institutions like the {{ill|Yin-Yang Bureau|lt=Yin-Yang Bureau|lt=Onmyōryō|ja|陰陽寮|1=Yin-Yang Bureau|2=ja|3=陰陽寮|4=fr|5=Bureau d'Onmyō|6=zh|7=阴阳寮|8=ko|9=음양료|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Onmyōryō|13=User:Immanuelle/Yin-Yang Bureau|qq=}} during the {{ill|Meiji Restoration|ja|明治維新|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Meiji Restoration|qq=}}. The government centralized calendrical functions under the Ministry of Education, diminishing the Tsuchimikado family's influence. Harenaga was briefly appointed as an official overseeing astronomical and calendrical affairs but lost this position when the government restructured these functions.
=== Political Career === Despite the decline of his family's traditional role, Harenaga remained active as a politician. In 1884, he was ennobled as a viscount under the new {{ill|kazoku|ja|華族|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/kazoku|qq=}} system. He served three terms as a member of the House of Peers, representing the viscount class, until his death in 1915.
